TEXT(beginproblem());

Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT
$PAR
For each of the indefinite integrals below, the main question is to decide whether 
the integral can be evaluated using \(u\)-substitution, integration by parts, a 
combination of the two, or neither.  For integrals for which your answer is affirmative, 
state the substitution(s) you would use.  It is not necessary to actually evaluate 
any of the integrals completely, unless the integral can be evaluated immediately 
using a familiar basic antiderivative. 
$PAR
\(\displaystyle \int x^2 \sin(x^3) \, dx\) \{ $mc[0]->menu() \} \{ ans_rule \} $BR
\(\displaystyle \int x^2 \sin(x) \, dx\) \{ $mc[1]->menu() \} \{ ans_rule \}$BR
\(\displaystyle \int \sin(x^3) \, dx\) \{ $mc[2]->menu() \} \{ ans_rule \}$BR
\(\displaystyle \int x^5 \sin(x^3) \, dx\) \{ $mc[3]->menu() \} \{ ans_rule \}$BR
$PAR
\(\displaystyle \int \frac{1}{1+x^2} \, dx\) \{ ans_rule \}$BR
\(\displaystyle \int \frac{x}{1+x^2} \, dx\) \{ ans_rule \}$BR
\(\displaystyle \int \frac{2x+3}{1+x^2} \, dx\) \{ ans_rule \}$BR
\(\displaystyle \int \frac{e^x}{1+(e^x)^2} \, dx\) \{ ans_rule \}$BR
$PAR
\(\displaystyle \int x \ln(x) \, dx\) \{ ans_rule \}$BR
\(\displaystyle \int \frac{\ln(x)}{x} \, dx\) \{ ans_rule \}$BR
\(\displaystyle \int \ln(1+x^2) \, dx\) \{ ans_rule \}$BR
\(\displaystyle \int x\ln(1+x^2) \, dx\) \{ ans_rule \}$BR
$PAR
\(\displaystyle \int x \sqrt{1-x^2} \, dx\) \{ ans_rule \}$BR
\(\displaystyle \int \frac{1}{\sqrt{1-x^2}} \, dx\) \{ ans_rule \}$BR
\(\displaystyle \int \frac{x}{\sqrt{1-x^2}}\, dx\) \{ ans_rule \}$BR
\(\displaystyle \int \frac{1}{x\sqrt{1-x^2}} \, dx\) \{ ans_rule \}$BR
$PAR




END_TEXT


